- Once upon a time in a certain country there lived a king whose palace was surrounded by a spacious garden. But, though the gardeners were many and the soil was good, this garden yielded neither flowers nor fruits, not even grass or shady trees. The King was in despair about it, when a wise old man said to him: “Your gardeners do not understand their business: but what can you expect of men whose fathers were cobblers and carpenters? How should they have learned to cultivate your garden?”
- Determined to transform his barren garden into a paradise, the King sought counsel from foreign lands; therefore, an enigmatic botanist named Elara who possessed an uncanny ability to communicate with the spirits of nature arrived at court eager to accept the challenge. But an eerie shadow seemed to tail her closely, whispering legends of a curse long ago placed on the earth beneath the palace grounds. This revelation left the King anxious yet intrigued—would Elara's peculiar powers be enough to unravel the mysterious curse that stifled life itself?
- Elara began her work with a midnight ritual, calling upon ancient spirits of nature to reveal the source of the curse, but as the ground trembled and shadows writhed, an unexpected voice emerged from the depths; it was the king's own great-grandmother, accused of jealousy and fear, who had enacted the curse in secret to safeguard her forgotten burial ground. The revelation ignited a predicament for the King—uncovering the secrets of his ancestors or risking his own credibility—but together, he and Elara resolved to confront both the potent spirit and the family's dark heritage in order to heal the forsaken soil.
